buildings.infoBoxString: The FHSU Soccer Facility is adjacent to the Bickle-Schmidt Sports Complex west of Highway 183 Alternate and south of old U.S. 40 Highway, west of the FHSU campus. The soccer facility was completed in 2011, and is now used by the men's and women's soccer teams.

Sheridan Coliseum was completed in 1917, and in 1922 the ceiling was installed. The building is named in honor of General Philip Sheridan who was stationed at the Fort Hays military post in the 1800s. Renovations were completed under President Hammond in 1991 with the help of a $750,000 gift by Ross & Marianna Beach and Bob & Pat Schmidt. A state-of-the-art performing arts center was included and was named the Beach/Schmidt Performing Arts Center in their honor. The 1,114-seat center ensured that Fort Hays State would continue to be the cultural center of western Kansas.
Offices presently housed in Sheridan Hall include: Administration & Finance, Budget & Planning, Business Office, Career Services, President's Office, Provost, Assistant Provost for Quality Management, Academic Affairs Marketing, Purchasing, Registrar, Student Affairs, Student Fiscal Services, and University Relations.

This 3-story Collegiate Gothic style limestone building was built in 1926 and originally named after General George A. Forsyth while it housed the university's library collection for about forty years. Initially, this building also housed offices, a few classrooms, a beautiful 2-story reading room on the north side, and the Museum of Natural History.
In 1967 the building was remodeled into an academic building after the library moved across the street. McCartney Hall gained its current name in 1968 in honor of Dr. Ernest Ray "E.R." McCartney, a long-time dean of the faculty and Professor of Economics and Business. The Sternberg Museum collections relocated across town in 1999 when the newly remodeled Beach Hall/Sternberg Museum opened. Today McCartney Hall houses the Dean of the College of Business and Entrepreneurship and the departments of Economics, Finance and Accounting, Employee Relations, Leadership Studies, and Management and Marketing.

Albertson Hall was built in 1928 and is easily recognizable by the observatory on top that houses a large telescope. The building is named for Dr. Frederick W. Albertson who came to Fort Hays in 1918 to teach agriculture and worked at the university for 43 years in various capacities. This building houses the office of the Dean of the College of Health & Behavioral Sciences, and the departments of Agriculture, Biological Sciences, and Communication Sciences and Disorders, as well as the Herndon Clinic.

As needs grew, a new dining space was constructed and financed by student fees alone at a cost of $851,600. The Memorial Union was completed and dedicated during Homecoming on October 18, 1958. In 2007 the Union was renovated at a cost of $8.5M to include the beautiful new entrance on the west side.
Today the Union serves as a gathering space for faculty, staff, students and the general public, and stands as a memorial to those of FHSU who lost their lives in the defense of their country during the two World Wars, the Korean conflict, and the Vietnam War. A bronze and walnut plaque in the Sunset Lounge in the Memorial Union lists the names of the FHSU men to whom the building was originally dedicated, and a memorial was added later for those who died in Vietnam.

buildings.buildingName: Sternberg Museum of Natural History (Beach Hall)
buildings.infoBoxString: Beach Hall is sited adjacent to Interstate 70 in the northeastern part of Hays. The domed portion of this building houses the world-famous Sternberg Museum. Beach Hall is named for Ross and Marianna Beach whose generous contributions helped make the renovation of the building possible. Here visitors can view the famous Fish-Within-A-Fish among the other exhibits.

The original power plant, constructed in 1911, was destroyed by fire in the winter of 1930. And soon after a new building was built in 1931 & 1932. The replacement building is now referred to as the Old Power Plant, and is presently used for Art Department studios and storage.

Initially called the Agricultural High School Building, and later the Industrial Building, Rarick Hall was first constructed in 1912. This building was razed in 1978, and the new Rarick Hall was completed in 1981. The building honors Dr. Clarence Edmund Rarick, who served as University President from 1933-1941 during the difficult times of the Great Depression and the Dust Bowl.
This academic building presently includes the Moss-Thorns Art Gallery and Tiger Tots Nursery Center and the departments of: Advanced Education Programs, Art, Business Education, English, History, Justice Studies, Mathematics, Modern Languages, Philosophy, Sociology and Social Work, and Teacher Education. The offices of the Dean of the College of Arts, Humanities, and Social Sciences and the Dean of the College of Education are also located in Rarick Hall.

The Social Building was built in 1905 during the presidency of William S. Picken. The gymnasium area was renovated into two-story space in 1960 to provide space for faculty offices, the print shop, student publications, and News Services. At that time, it was renamed Martin Allen Hall in honor of the pioneer who first called for an agricultural college on the old military reservation. Martin Allen Hall is presently home to the Psychology department.

Fort Hays State University's first structure was constructed in 1904 and originally known as the Academic Hall and later as the Administration Building. Picken Hall served primarily as a classroom building until the 1980's when new campus buildings were constructed. The building honors William S. Picken who was named principal of the western branch of the Kansas State Normal School at Hays City when the school was founded in 1902.
The building houses Admissions, Financial Assistance, the Registrar, Academic Advising & Career Exploration, the Kelly Center, the Graduate School, and Student Fiscal Services.

Constructed in 1981, Stroup Hall provides classrooms, labs and offices for the Nursing department, and is named in honor of Leora B. Stroup, director of the nursing program. The nursing program was established on the 50th anniversary of the founding of the college on September 1, 1952. Initially, the Nursing department had the use of two rooms on campus and consisted of one faculty member (Miss Stroup), sixteen students and three courses.

It was during the years of Dr. M. C. Cunningham's tenure as president of Fort Hays Kansas State College that the state legislature appropriated $50,000 to build a house on campus for the president's residence. Sited on the west edge of the main campus, this home has provided living accommodations for the families of Dr. Cunningham, Dr. John W. Gustad, Dr. Gerald W. Tomanek, Dr. Edward H. Hammond, Dr. Mirta M. Martin, and Dr. Tisa Mason since its completion in late summer of 1954.

Malloy Hall was built in 1965 during the presidency of Dr. M. C. Cunningham, and is named for Henry Edward Malloy who was employed by the university in 1913 to teach chorus. This building is presently home to the departments of Music, Communication Studies, Journalism, Student Publications and Theatre. Palmer Hall, a 110-seat classroom and musical performance area, and the Felten Start Theatre, with a seating capacity of 316, are also located in Malloy Hall.

Forsyth Library was finished in 1974 and named after military leader General George A. Forsyth, who was stationed at old Fort Hays in the 1880s.

The library collection, first housed in the old fort hospital building in 1902, then moved to Picken Hall, Martin Allen Hall, McCartney Hall, and finally to this building, has grown from 702 volumes to over 14,000 volumes. The collection sustained major damage in May of 1951 when sixteen inches of water flooded into the first floor of the library.

Here students can find the writing center, Tiger Food Exchange, and many more resources.

After being moved from Russell County to Hays for permanent restoration, the Plymouth Schoolhouse is now a major attraction on the Fort Hays State University campus. The Fort Hays State University Chapter of Phi Delta Kappa completed the restoration of the building in 1979.
The building is located across the street from Tomanek Hall and attracts more than 1,000 visitors each year.

Built in 1995, this uniquely designed structure was named for Dr. Gerald W. Tomanek, the seventh University President serving from 1976-1987. It is comprised of 98,867 gross square feet and was recognized for its design excellence. Today Tomanek Hall houses the Computing and Telecommunications Center and the departments of Chemistry, Geosciences, and Physics. It is also home to the skeleton of Al the dinosaur and our giant pendulum.

Nestled on the banks of Big Creek between Tomanek Hall and Gross/Cunningham Hall, Hammond Hall currently houses the office of the Dean of the Werth College of Science, Technology and Mathematics, and the departments of Informatics, Computer Science, the Virtual College, and the Office of University Relations and Marketing.
Hammond Hall is dedicated to Dr. Edward H. Hammond, the eighth president of Fort Hays State University. He was the longest serving president in the Kansas Board of Regents system and the longest serving president in the 110-year history of FHSU.

Known for many years as simply the New Power Plant, this building was built in 1968, replacing the previous Power Plant located on the north side of campus. The Akers Energy Center is named in honor of Dale L. Akers, former Physical Plant Director. The dedication and renaming of the building took place in 1991.
The Switchgear Building is used as a maintenance building for facility use.

The first wing of Custer Hall was completed in 1922, and a second wing was added in 1952 followed by an elevator in 1998. The building is named after Elizabeth Custer, the wife of General George Armstrong Custer. Presently, the building is the residence space for high school students enrolled in the Kansas Academy of Mathematics and Science and its administrative offices, the University Police Department, and the Kansas Small Business Development Regional Center.

This six-story building was built in the 1960s and now provides co-educational living accommodations for approximately 500 students. Dining services for all residential life facilities are provided in the newly renovated cafeteria area.
McMindes Hall is named in honor of Professor Maude M. McMindes who served as the Director of Secondary Teacher Training and Director of Student Teaching.

Heather Hall opened in the Fall of 2013 as one of FHSU's newest dormitories, with beds for 112 students. The building is named in honor of Jack R. Heather who was employed by President Cunningham in 1950 to develop the radio curriculum and provide proper experience and training for the broadcasting industry.

Agnew Hall opened its doors for co-ed living in the fall of 2012 with beds for 123 students, arranged in 4-bedroom suites. It was constructed on the same site that the original Agnew Hall occupied. Agnew Hall was named after Elizabeth Jane Agnew who was employed to teach domestic economy (Home Economics) in 1910 and who stayed on to eventually become Dean of Women before her retirement in 1943.

In January, 1961, construction began on the first married students' apartments. Today, the 84 apartments in the 6 buildings of Wooster Place are no longer restricted to married students and their families. Both one- and two-bedroom apartments are available for rent. All apartments were renovated from 2003 - 2005. The apartments are named in honor of university president, President Lyman Dwight Wooster. Dr. Wooster began employment with the university as a faculty member in 1909 and taught for 32 years.

In January, 1961, construction began on the first married students' apartments. Today, the 84 apartments in the 6 buildings of Wooster Place are no longer restricted to married students and their families. Both one- and two-bedroom apartments are available for rent. All apartments were renovated from 2003 - 2005. The apartments are named in honor of university president, President Lyman Dwight Wooster. Dr. Wooster began employment with the university as a faculty member in 1909 and taught for 32 years.

Victor E. Village is one of our newest residential halls. This building opened in the Fall of 2017 and replaced the old Wiest Hall. It has 406 beds with pod style bathrooms, an Italian fast food option called 2matos, and a convenience store. This residence hall also includes a kitchen and dining room, 2 recreation rooms, laundry facilities, 8 social lounges, 8 study rooms, and a conference room. This hall is designed for first year Living and Learning Community students who share a common major or interest.

The Dane G. Hansen Scholarship Hall is funded by a generous gift from the Dane G. Hansen Foundation. The Scholarship Hall opened for residence for a select group of only 33 students in the Fall of 2016 and provides individual private rooms with many facility amenities including an eLab classroom space, innovation and maker space, student study lounges, high speed fiber connectivity, and a mini-kitchen with free laundry facilities. It is desgined as a living and learning community for students who have demonstrated a passion for entrepreneurship regardless of their academic major. Students from any academic major interested in entrepreneurship can apply to live in this beautiful new residential building.

The four buildings of Stadium Place apartments were contructed in 2005. These two 2-story and two 3-story buildings hold two-bedroom and four-bedroom apartments to accommodate 118 students. The apartments are located near Lewis Field Stadium where McGrath Hall once stood. Each of the four buildings honors someone who figured prominently in FHSU history and had a great impact in the lives of students. From the North to the South the apartments honor Billy D. Jellison - who dedicated 28 years to providing guidance and support for students at Fort Hays State University, William D. Moreland - who served Fort Hays Kansas State College in several capacities from 1953 to 1969, Nita M. Landrum and her 30-year tenure at Fort Hays Kansas State College, and Robert T. McGrath - who served as head of the Department of Education and Director of Teacher Training in the 1930s.

This new three-story building on campus was recently opened in the Fall of 2017. This residence is the home of four unique houses of 24 students each, including Delta Zeta, Sigma Sigma Sigma, Sigma Phi Epsilon, and the Sophomore Experience/Transfer Network Living Learning Community.

Lewis Field Stadium began in 1930s and was added to in 1997 and 2001. The orginal design of the stadium included space beneath the seats and press box for living, recreational, and study space. The old cinder track was replaced in the 1993 and was officially named the Alex Francis Track. Lewis Field Stadium is named for university president, William A. Lewis who served the university from 1913-1933.

Situated adjacent to Lewis Field Stadium, the Schmidt-Bickle Training Facility was completed in July, 2013. This 50,000 sq. ft. indoor training facility features a multisport practice field, indoor batting cages, 5 seventy-yard track lanes, long jump, high jump, and pole vault pits, and a state-of-the-art weight room. Athletes from various sports are able to train year-round in this new facility which expands the athletic training area available at Cunningham Hall/Gross Coliseum. The building honors the contributions of two local couples: Bob and Pat Schmidt and Don and Chris Bickle.
The South Maintenance Building is used as a maintenance building for facility use.

The Center for Applied Technology and Sculpture is our newest academic building on campus and home to both the Applied Technology department and the Art and Design Sculpture program. This two-story building holds 58,000 square feet of computer CAD, instuctional & graphics, STEM, woodworking, metalworking, plastics, power & energy, robotics, and construction managment labs, as well as sculpture and metal foundry studios.

Built in 1960, the Motor Pool building provides shop space to service vehicles, a wash bay, office space, garage space for vehicles and a storage area. The Motor Pool provides vehicles for university employees to use for official state business travel. The fleet includes sedans, mini-vans, 8-passenger vans, 12-passenger vans, and a pickup.

The Grounds Building was built in 1960, and the present greenhouse was built in 1998. The east side of the greenhouse is used for Biological Sciences and Agriculture department research. The west side of the greenhouse is used to propagate plants for the flower beds on campus. In season, bananas may be observed growing on the banana tree there.

The Brooks Building was originally the Art Annex, built in 1968 to house classrooms for ceramics, painting, sculpture and drawing classes. When the art department vacated the building in 1981 and moved into Rarick Hall, the building was remodeled into office space. Departments housed in the building presently include Printing Services, Physical Plant, Facilities Planning, Environment/Safety, and Custodial Services. The R.U. Brooks Building is named for Raymond Brooks who joined the FHSU faculty in 1935 and served as Superintendent of Buildings and Professor of Industrial Education.

The C.A. Witt Maintenance Building was built in 1960 and was expanded in 1997 to include an extra shop space on the south end. It provides work space for the lock shop, carpentry, painting, welding, HVAC shops and construction crew offices, telecommunications technicians, the Central Purchasing department, and a meats fabrication lab. The meats lab is utilized for the Agriculture Department class, Consumer's Guide to the Meat Industry, to fabricate beef, pork and lamb carcasses into retail cuts for sale to the public. The meats lab is also used by the basic Animal Science Class and the Livestock Selection and Evaluation classes to assess quality, yield, and palatability characteristics of the product derived from a live animal. The C.A. Witt Building was named in honor of Cliff Witt, a maintenance engineer who served FHSU for almost 30 years.

The Fort Hays State University Foundation and the Alumni Association share the beautiful Robbins Center which opened in 2007. The Robbins Center is named in honor of W.R. (Bill) and Yvonne Robbins, one of seven lead donors who had committed $2M for the building project: Bill and Yvonne Robbins, Great Bend; Darrel and Dee Rolph, Wichita; Jim Thurman, Great Bend; Richard Diamond, Mankato; the Don and Cecilia Bickle family, Hays; Bob and Pat Schmidt, Hays; and the late Dale Shade, Hays.

The sports complex including Gross Coliseum and Cunningham Hall was constructed in 1973. Gross Coliseum houses the basketball arena and running track. Seating is available in Gross Coliseum for 6,196 spectators in the balcony and bleacher areas. The facility accommodates approximately 1,400 more people at Commencement ceremonies when seating is arranged on the Coliseum floor for graduates and handicapped seating. Gross Coliseum is named for Paul "Busch" Gross who was employed by the university in 1934 as a backfield coach in the football program and as head basketball coach after having been a student athlete himself.

Built in 1973, Cunningham Hall was part of the sports complex that included Gross Coliseum, housing four gymnasiums and five racquetball courts. A Wellness Center, swimming pool, locker rooms and offices occupy the rest of the space in Cunningham Hall. Departments housed in the complex include Athletics, Health & Human Performance, Allied Health, and Gross/Cunningham Operations. Cunningham Hall was named for Dr. Morton Christy Cunningham, known as the "Builder President," the fifth administrative head of the Fort Hays Kansas State College.

pois.title: Memorial Union
pois.infoBoxString: Dining facilities for students were first provided in 1909 within the old Infirmary Building, which had been relocated to campus from old Fort Hays, and in 1912, was moved to the new Agricultural High School Building (the first Rarick Hall). As dining needs continued to grow, Cody Commons was constructed in 1923 in the location of the present day Memorial Union kitchen/dining area. At a cost of $851,600, student fees alone financed the construction of the Memorial Union which was completed and dedicated during Homecoming on October 18, 1958. In 2007 the Union was renovated at a cost of $8.5M to include the beautiful new entrance on the west side. The building serves as a gathering space for faculty, staff, students and the general public, and stands as a memorial to those of FHSU who lost their lives in the defense of their country during the two world wars, the Korean conflict, and the Vietnam War. A bronze and walnut plaque in the Sunset Lounge in the Memorial Union lists the names of the FHSU men to whom the building was originally dedicated, and a memorial was added later next to the Memorial Union for those who died in Vietnam.

pois.title: Robbins Center
pois.infoBoxString: The Fort Hays State University Foundation and the Alumni Association share the beautiful Robbins Center which opened in 2007. The Robbins Center is named in honor of W.R. (Bill) and Yvonne Robbins, one of seven lead donors who had committed $2M for the building project: Bill and Yvonne Robbins, Great Bend; Darrel and Dee Rolph, Wichita; Jim Thurman, Great Bend; Richard Diamond, Mankato; the Don and Cecilia Bickle family, Hays; Bob and Pat Schmidt, Hays; and the late Dale Shade, Hays.

pois.title: FHSU Historical Introduction
pois.infoBoxString: Fort Hays State University was founded in 1902 with 34 students, two faculty members, and 19 courses. Today Fort Hays has approximately 14,000 students (4,800 on-campus) and 827 faculty and staff members. We were recently recognized as the 3rd fastest growing University in the nation.

pois.title: The Quad
pois.infoBoxString: The quad is a terrific area for students to congregate and socialize. There are many events hosted in the quad throughout the year, including the back to school picnic, Greek Week Activities, Jamaican Me Crazy Luau, a Cinco De Mayo celebration on the patio, some of the University Activities Board Creation Stations like T-Shirt Tie-Dye and Paint Your Own Flower Pot.

pois.title: Memorial Union
pois.infoBoxString: The Memorial Union, built in 1958 and renovated in 2007, serves as the "Community Center for the campus". Just inside the main west doors of the Union are 6 murals called "The Journey" which signify the Journey of our University over the past 114 years. The Memorial Union is also home to the Sunset Lounge, Bookstore, Food Court, Starbucks, Cody Commons, Student Health, and offices for SGA, CSI, and UAB.

pois.title: FHSU Bronzed Tiger
pois.infoBoxString: The bronzed Tiger replica was created by FHSU instructor of sculpture, Toby Flores, and his sculpting students in 10 months for the grand re-opening of the Memorial Union in 2007.

pois.title: McMindes Hall & Cafe
pois.infoBoxString: Each wing and floor in McMindes Hall is overseen by a Residential Advisor who lives on that floor and is trained to aid hall residents in the transition to college. Each hall also has a live-in Hall Director as well as other professional staff. McMindes Hall houses approximately 600 residents and is also home to the buffet-style Cafe where students can enjoy their meals.

pois.title: The 2 Wind Turbines
pois.infoBoxString: Our wind turbines provide energy directly to campus, and their combined energy covers roughly 97% of our energy consumption. This translates to an annual reduction of $600,000 to $1 million in energy costs per year for FHSU. The two turbines stand 400 feet tall and are located just west of Hays.

pois.title: Forsyth Library
pois.infoBoxString: Forsyth Library was completed in 1967 with three floors of books, reference materials, journals, magazines, and other materials available for students to check out. Throughout Forsyth are study rooms, whiteboards, computers, and desk space for students to work. Forsyth also provides inter-library loan services and research and writing assistance at the Research Help Desk and the Writing Center. The One Stop Shop, which allows students to borrow equipment like laptops, cameras, and projectors, and the Learning Commons, which helps students with the technology applications they use in the classroom, are also housed in Forsyth. The Tiger Food Exchange, Makerspace, Internatonal Student Service center, Study Abroad program, and offices for the Honors College are all located throughout Forsyth as well.

pois.title: Tomanek Hall
pois.infoBoxString: Tomanek Hall is one of FHSU's Academic buildings and is home to the Chemistry, Geo-sciences, and Physics & Pre-Engineering Departments, as well as a few FHSU treasures including the Foucault Pendulum, which demonstrates the rotation of the earth, and 'Al' the Allosaurus, which was discovered in Utah by a group of geology students. Tomanek is also where students can find the TigerTech Service Desk and get technological assistance.

pois.title: Tiger Bookshop
pois.infoBoxString: Across the street from Picken Hall is the Tiger Book Shop, another bookstore that carries FHSU textbooks and apparel.

circles.name: Wooster Place
circles.infoWindowContent: Wooster Place apartments offer the benefits of on-campus living with modern amenities. Family friendly, but open to FHSU upperclassmen as well, Wooster Place offers both one- and two-bedroom apartments. Each residence includes a full kitchen, living room, bathroom, and bedrooms.

polygons.name: Main Administrative buildings
polygons.infoBoxString: Sheridan Hall and Picken Hall are the main administrative buildings at FHSU
